[[File:ITU-Secretary-General-Hamadoun-Toure.jpg|thumb|Official portrait of Hamadoun Touré, Secretary General of the International Telecommunication Union]]
'''Hamadoun Touré''' (born September 3, 1953)<ref>http://www.everywomaneverychild.org/resources/accountability-commission/chairs/dr-hamadoun-toure</ref> of [[Mali]] was Secretary General of the [[International Telecommunication Union]] (ITU), the [[specialized agencies|specialized agency]] of the [[United Nations]] dedicated to information and communication technologies (ICTs), from 2007 to December 2014. He was re-elected for a second four-year term in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itu.int/net/ITU-SG/index.aspx |title=Office of the Secretary General |publisher=Itu.int |date= |accessdate=2012-05-15}}</ref>  Since 2007, he has worked to fulfil ITU's mandate to 'connect the world' and help achieve the Millennium Development Goals. He actively promoted the ITU Connect series of events, with the first one, [[Connect Africa]], being held in [[Kigali]], [[Rwanda]], in 2007. Connect Africa raised US$55 billion in investment pledges to improve Africa's telecommunications infrastructure over seven years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://downloads.pcworld.about.com/businesscenter/article/144718/itu_nets_55_billion_for_connect_africa_launch.html |title=About.com: Need. Know. Accomplish |publisher=Downloads.pcworld.about.com |date=2011-07-07 |accessdate=2012-05-15}}</ref> In the first two years, 2008 and 2009, US$22 billion was invested in ICT infrastructure, mainly for mobile communications.

Touré serves as co-vice-chair of the [[Broadband Commission for Digital Development]] which was launched in May 2010 by ITU and [[UNESCO]], with Paul Kagame, President of Rwanda, and Carlos Slim Helú, Honorary Lifetime Chairman of Grupo Carso, as co-chairs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.broadbandcommission.org |title=Broadband Commission for Digital Development |publisher=Broadbandcommission.org |accessdate=}}</ref>

He is also on the [[International Multilateral Partnership Against Cyber Threats]] (IMPACT) International Advisory Board <ref>http://www.impact-alliance.org/aboutus/profile-of-IAB-members.html</ref>

In May 2011, IMPACT has been appointed the United Nation’s (UN) Cybersecurity Executing Arm by the UN’s Specialised Agency – International Telecommunication Union (ITU). The Memorandum of Agreement was officially signed by Hamadoun Touré and [[Mohd Noor Amin|Datuk Mohd Noor Amin]], Chairman of IMPACT at the ITU’s head office in Geneva.<ref>http://it.tmcnet.com/topics/it/articles/223220-impact-appointed-uns-cybersecurity-executing-arm-un-specialized.htm</ref>

==Biography==
Hamadoun Touré was born in 1953 in the [[Republic of Mali]]. He studied at the [[St. Petersburg State University of Telecommunications|Technical Institute of Electronics and Telecommunication of Leningrad]] (LEIS), receiving a master's degree in [[electrical engineering]], and a [[Candidate of Sciences]] degree (equivalent to PhD) from the {{Interlanguage link multi|Moscow Technical University of Communication and Informatics|ru|3=Московский технический университет связи и информатики}} ([[MTUCI]]), in [[Russia]]. Touré was Director of ITU's Telecommunication Development Bureau from 1998 to 2006. Prior to joining ITU he had a distinguished career in the satellite industry. Touré also is a licensed radio amateur with the call sign HB9EHT.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arrl.org/itu |title=The International Telecommunications Union |publisher=ARRL |date= |accessdate=2013-01-12}}</ref> Touré is married, with four children and two grandchildren.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itu.int/en/osg/Pages/biography.aspx |title=Biography |publisher=Itu.int |date=2012-02-09 |accessdate=2012-05-15}}</ref>

